"""constants.py — leaf module: the daemon's load-bearing constants.

Extracted (DA-CONST-01, daemon-architecture-v2) so version/port config
lives in a dependency-free leaf that ANY module can import without a
cycle back to daemon.py — unblocking the selfupdate/bootstrap splits.
No sibling imports. bundle.py reads DAEMON_VERSION from HERE for the
early 8 KB version marker; MODULES inlines constants.py FIRST.
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import os
from pathlib import Path


PORT_RANGE = (5570, 5589)

# Release-signing PUBLIC key (Ed25519, hex). py-1.27.5. The daemon verifies
# every self-update bundle's detached signature (`<url>.sig`) against this
# pinned key before swapping + re-exec'ing — so a CDN compromise / MITM
# can't push code that runs as the operator. The matching PRIVATE seed
# lives ONLY at daemon/.release-signing-key (gitignored, off-CDN) and is
# used by bundle.py at release time. Rotating the key = regenerate the
# seed, re-pin this hex, redeploy (old daemons that already trust the old
# key will reject the new build until they update through a key-overlap
# release — see workflows/W2). Empty string = signature checks disabled.
RELEASE_PUBKEY_HEX = "9699b5c93066195d85e974a1bca9ace6931ea31a21e347414d6f0a34d55b13cb"
# py-1.15.0 — machine-global sticky port registry (cluster_id → port).
# Lives outside any repo so every daemon on this box shares one source of
# truth and a cluster ALWAYS comes back up on the same port (no drift).
# py-1.16.0 (D-TEST-ISO-01) — MESHKORE_PORTS_FILE overrides the registry
# path so the test suite (which spawns real daemon subprocesses) points it
# at a tmp file instead of polluting the operator's real ~/.meshkore.
_PORT_REGISTRY_FILE = Path(
    os.environ.get("MESHKORE_PORTS_FILE") or (Path.home() / ".meshkore" / "ports.json")
)
_PORT_REGISTRY_DIR = _PORT_REGISTRY_FILE.parent
FS_POLL_SEC = 1.5
DAEMON_VERSION = "py-1.31.2"  # 1.31.2 — MULTI-CLI-CLIENTS FOLLOW-UP #2 (same live-smoke-test session as 1.31.1). PATCHing the codex smoke-test member's `model` to `""` (the correct empty-model sentinel per 1.31.1's own fix) round-tripped to `model: {}` on the very next GET — an empty MAPPING, not an empty string. Root cause: `team.py:serialise_member()` wrote a bare `key:` with nothing after the colon for an empty-string value; this project's simplified YAML parser treats "nothing on this line" as "the value is a nested block starting below" (same heuristic real YAML uses for block mappings), so it read back as `{}`. No prior field had ever legitimately held an empty string (every other optional field's default is a non-empty sentinel like `default`/`internal`), so this never surfaced before the multi-cli-clients empty-model case existed. Fixed: `serialise_member` now explicitly quotes an empty value as `""` for ANY field, not just the fields in `_QUOTED_FIELDS`. New `test_serialise_roundtrip_preserves_empty_model_as_string`. Suite: 330 passed. 1.31.1 — MULTI-CLI-CLIENTS FOLLOW-UP (live smoke test on the just-shipped py-1.31.0, same day). Dispatched a real member with `client: codex` through the FULL daemon path (not just the raw CLI spike) and found two real bugs unit tests with synthesized data hadn't caught: (a) `CodexDriver.parse_stream_line` didn't recognize `{"type":"error"}`/`{"type":"turn.failed"}` events at all — an invalid `-m <model>` for the account produced a clean `exit=1` with COMPLETELY EMPTY final text, no diagnostic anywhere. Fixed: both event types now surface their message as `Final(text="[codex error] ...")`, mirroring claude-code's own "API Error: ..." final-text convention (and interacting correctly with `is_transient_error`'s existing marker allowlist — a 400 invalid-request is correctly NOT retried). (b) `team.py`'s `_normalise_payload` unconditionally defaulted an omitted `model` to `opus` (the claude-code strongest-alias sentinel) regardless of `client` — creating a `client: codex` member with no explicit model produced `-m opus`, which Codex rejects outright ("not supported when using Codex with a ChatGPT account"). Fixed: the default is now driver-relative — a client whose OWN `models_catalog()` declares `""` as a legitimate "use account default" entry (codex, gemini) gets an empty model when omitted; claude-code (no such catalog entry) is completely unchanged. `validate_member`'s "model is mandatory" check gets the same driver-relative exemption. Also fixed 3 more hardcoded `claude(...)` log-line labels in `runnerloop.py` missed in 1.31.0 (cosmetic — log messages now correctly show which client actually ran). New tests: `test_parse_error_and_turn_failed_surface_as_final_text` (real captured error/turn.failed NDJSON) + `tests/test_team_client_model.py` (9 cases pinning the per-client model-default/validation behavior). Suite: 329 passed. 1.31.0 — MULTI-CLI-CLIENTS (initiative `multi-cli-clients`). Team members can now be dispatched via Claude Code (default, unchanged), Gemini CLI, or Codex CLI, selected per member. New `clidrivers/` package: a `ClientDriver` interface (find_binary/auth_configured/models_catalog/efforts_catalog/build_args/write_prompt/parse_stream_line/is_transient_error) with `ClaudeCodeDriver` a VERBATIM extraction of the pre-existing spawn/parse logic (zero behavior change — the full suite's count never dropped through the whole refactor), plus new `GeminiDriver`/`CodexDriver`. `parse_stream_line()` normalizes each client's raw stdout into 4 shapes (TextDelta/ToolUse/ToolResult/Final) that `runnerloop.py` already understood — anchor-marker buffering, tool-timeline persistence, usage/cost capture all stayed generic and untouched, so they work for any driver "for free". `team.py` gained a `client` field (absent = claude-code, zero migration for existing members); `effort` validation is now driver-relative (delegates to the resolved driver's own `efforts_catalog()`) instead of one hardcoded global enum. `convmeta.py`/`teamsvc.py`/`chatspawn.py`/`chatsvc.py`/`chatread.py` thread `client` through dispatch end-to-end, mirroring the existing `model`/`effort` plumbing exactly. New `GET /clients` (no auth, like `/agents`) returns each registered driver's `{id, label, installed, authConfigured, models, efforts}` — installed/auth are LIVE local probes (shutil.which + env/credentials-file presence), never cached. Real-world findings from live-testing on the operator's machine (not assumed from docs): Codex CLI's `codex exec --json` survives the daemon's exact spawn shape (piped stdin, no TTY) cleanly — spike passed, real NDJSON captured and used verbatim in `test_clidrivers_codex.py` — but does NOT stream token-level deltas (whole message per `item.completed`), and tool calls map cleanly to `command_execution` items. Gemini CLI 0.49.0 (installed fresh to verify) has NO CLI-level reasoning-effort flag at all — pre-implementation research claiming one existed was wrong; `GeminiDriver.efforts_catalog()` honestly reflects a single no-op `default`. Gemini's `parse_stream_line()` remains a best-effort guess (no `GEMINI_API_KEY` on this machine to capture real output) — flagged explicitly in code + task file, not silently assumed correct. Architect cockpit: Client picker in `NewMemberDialog`/`MemberDetailPanel` (dynamic model/effort catalog per client, sourced from `/clients`, with graceful fallback to the existing claude-code-only catalog when an older daemon 404s), non-default-client roster badge, catalog-aware `ChatScopeStrip` inline pickers. Explicitly NOT done (documented, not silent scope creep): no cross-turn native session/resume for any client (fresh spawn per turn, daemon owns history via the briefing — unchanged from today); no tool-call UI fidelity GUARANTEE for non-Claude clients (text-only is the hard requirement); no live upstream model-list fetching (catalogs are static, updated via normal version bumps); no per-member credential-setup UI (cockpit only reports installed/auth state). Full daemon suite: 297→320 passed across every step (22 new driver tests), never regressed. 1.30.4 — TEAM-EXT CAP + STALE-REQUEST SELF-HEAL, PORT-STABILITY DOC FIX. Two independent fixes from the same 2026-07-08 incident (a shared-daemon port restart broke an external `consultant` integration). (a) `teamext.py`: a watcher thread has no persisted registry of its own — when the daemon process dies mid-turn (crash, `/shutdown`, a port-changing restart), the thread dies with it and the request sits `running`/`queued` in `team-requests.json` forever, silently eating an `EXT_ASK_CONCURRENT_CAP` slot until the 24h GC eventually erases it outright. New `_teamext_reap_stale()` flips any `queued`/`running` entry older than `_WATCH_MAX_SECS` (1h — no legitimate watcher survives past its own hard-timeout) to `error`, called at both read sites (the ask handler's cap check, and the `GET /team/requests/<id>` poll) so a client polling an orphan sees a terminal status instead of hanging, and the cap slot frees immediately instead of after 24h. Also raised `EXT_ASK_CONCURRENT_CAP` 2→6 — a single local operator legitimately fires several ask/poll probes back-to-back while debugging; 2 was tight enough that one orphan alone locked the member out. (b) `scaffold.py`: the generated `cluster.yaml`'s transport comment claimed "it may shift between restarts — that is normal", which was already false as of py-1.15.0's sticky-port registry (D-PORT-01) but nobody had corrected the template — misleading enough that a real port drift (this incident) wasn't suspected as a bug. Comment rewritten to describe the actual sticky behavior; new templated `architect.port` block seeds `_pick_port`'s from-scratch fallback so a wiped registry (or first boot on a new machine) still lands on a durable, intentional value instead of "first free port in range" musical chairs. Neither change touches the wire protocol or `_pick_port`'s core algorithm — pure guard-rail + docs. 1.30.3 — SERVER-HOME NEVER A PROJECT (durable, env-independent). The central daemon's own home (`meshkore-server` — its `.meshkore` IS the machine-global store: ideas, projects registry, external creds) kept leaking into /projects + the cockpit rail as if it were a project. Root cause: the only exclusion signal was the STRUCTURAL test `_is_home_context` (compares the context root's `.meshkore` to the global-ledger root) — which DEPENDS on how the daemon was launched: if `MESHKORE_GLOBAL_ROOT` doesn't resolve to the home's `.meshkore`, the test returns False and the home shows up as a project. That's why it "came back" after every differently-launched restart. FIX: a hardcoded id denylist backstop (projectsapi `_DEFAULT_HOME_IDS={'meshkore-server'}`, extendable per machine via `MESHKORE_HOME_IDS`) combined with the structural test in a single `is_home(pid, root)` gate applied on EVERY /projects path — `_real_project_ids`/`projects_list` (exclude), `rehydrate_projects` (never re-register a home from a stale projects.json + `_prune_home_from_projects` self-heal), `project_register` (409 refuse — the home can't be adopted). readapi `/health.server_home` now also ORs the id denylist so the cockpit gets a reliable signal regardless of launch flags. Cockpit `known-projects.ts` hardcodes the same id in its home set (belt-and-suspenders — the rail filters it even if a /health signal is ever missed). Pure exclusion/guard logic — no wire/schema change. tests/test_multiproject: `test_server_home_id_backstop` proves exclusion when the structural test is blind. 1.30.2 — TEAM-EXT AUTO-ARCHIVE (initiative `team-external-gateway` follow-up). External asks to a PROFILE member (consultant, etc.) were never archived once their turn finished, so `ext-<member>-<session|stamp>` convs piled up forever as non-archived rows and cluttered the operator's chat-rail agents column (they are one-shot/session API artifacts, not operator-facing sessions). `teamext.py` `_teamext_watch` now takes an `auto_archive` flag (true for `kind: profile`, false for singletons — architect-master/roadmap-orchestrator keep their ONE visible working conversation by design) and archives the conv in the watcher's `finally` block, covering all three terminal paths (done, idle-timeout error, watch-deadline error) plus any unexpected exception. Archiving is cosmetic only — `chat_dispatch` never checks the archived flag, so a later ask on the SAME `session` still works exactly as before (it just re-archives on completion); History → Archived still shows every one. No Standard bump (daemon-local capability, mirrors how TEG-2/CPL-1 shipped).
